<worksheet label="ws-act-2-4-2">
  <page>
    <activity xml:id="act-2-4-2" workspace="3cm">
      <introduction>
        <p>
      Let <m>p(x) = \csc(x)</m> and recall that <m>\csc(x) = \frac{1}{\sin(x)}</m>.

      </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="2cm" xml:id="act-2-4-2-task-0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the domain of <m>p</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            For what values of <m>x</m> is <m>\sin(x) = 0</m>?
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p>
            All real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \ne k\pi</m>,
            where <m>k = 0, \pm 1, \pm 2, \ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p><m>p(x) = \csc(x)</m> is defined for all <m>x</m> for which <m>\sin(x) \ne 0</m>.
            Hence the domain of <m>h</m> is all real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \ne k\pi</m>,
            where <m>k = 0, \pm 1, \pm 2, \ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="7.5cm" xml:id="act-2-4-2-task-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the quotient rule to develop a formula for <m>p'(x)</m> that is expressed completely in terms of <m>\sin(x)</m> and <m>\cos(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Don't forget that <m>\frac{d}{dx}[1] = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p><m> h'(x) = -\frac{\cos(x)}{\sin^2(x)}</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            By the quotient rule,
            <me>
              h'(x) = \frac{0 - 1 \cdot (\cos(x))}{\sin^2(x)} = -\frac{\cos(x)}{\sin^2(x)}
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-2-4-2-task-2">
        <statement>
          <p>
            How can you use other relationships among trigonometric functions to write <m>p'(x)</m> only in terms of <m>\cot(x)</m> and <m>\csc(x)</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Consider rewriting <m>\frac{\cos(x)}{\sin^2(x)}</m> as <m>\frac{1}{\sin(x)} \cdot \frac{\cos(x)}{\sin(x)}</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p><m> h'(x) = -\csc(x) \cot(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Observe that <m>h'(x) = -\frac{\cos(x)}{\sin^2(x)} = -\frac{1}{\sin(x)} \cdot \frac{\cos(x)}{\sin(x)}</m>, so
            <me>
              h'(x) = -\csc(x) \cot(x)
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-2-4-2-task-3">
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the domain of <m>p'</m>?
            How does this compare to the domain of <m>p</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            Observe that <m>\sin(x)</m> is still present in the denominator of <m>h'(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
        <answer>
          <p><m>p</m> and <m>p'</m> have the same domain:
            all real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \ne k\pi</m>,
            where <m>k = 0, \pm 1, \pm 2, \ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The derivative <m>p'(x)</m> is, like <m>p(x)</m>,
            defined for all values of <m>x</m> for which <m>\sin(x) \ne 0</m>.
            Therefore, <m>p</m> and <m>p'</m> have the same domain:
            all real numbers <m>x</m> such that <m>x \ne k\pi</m>,
            where <m>k = 0, \pm 1, \pm 2, \ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </activity>
  </page>
</worksheet>
